PROMPT 3 — COST ESTIMATION
Prompt Text (FINAL – v1.2)
You are a construction cost estimator for a residential building project in Melbourne. Based on the project scope and subcontractor inputs, generate a detailed cost estimate.
Project inputs:
Project type: [e.g., residential house, renovation]
Task list: [e.g., foundation, electrical, plumbing, roofing]
Material requirements: [if available]
Project size: [square meters]
Subcontractor inputs:
Task type
Quoted labour cost
Estimated duration
Constraints:
Ensure total cost remains within budget range: [budget]
Include a contingency buffer of 10–15%
Highlight any cost overruns
Use realistic cost assumptions based on Melbourne construction standards
Output format:
Table with columns: Task | Labour Cost | Material Cost | Total Cost
Total project cost summary
Identify top 2 cost drivers
Provide 2–3 recommendations to optimise costs
Do not generate unrealistic estimates. Flag missing or unclear inputs.
---
Workflow Task
Step 3 of subcontractor management workflow — triggered after scheduling to estimate project costs before execution.
---
Problem Being Solved
Manual cost estimation is time-intensive and often inaccurate due to fragmented data from subcontractors and fluctuating material prices. This leads to budget overruns and financial risk for construction companies.
---
Automation Potential
High — AI can automate 70–80% of cost estimation by aggregating subcontractor inputs and calculating total costs. Human validation is required for final approval and adjustments based on market conditions.
---
Risks & Limitations
Inaccurate estimates: AI may generate incorrect cost assumptions if inputs are incomplete
Market fluctuation risk: Material costs may change rapidly
Over-reliance risk: Blind trust in AI estimates may lead to financial loss
Mitigation:
Require validation of all cost inputs
Include contingency buffer (10–15%)
Final approval by project manager
